profile.title: MD
profile.bio: I was born and raised in the suburbs of New York City. I attended Brown University for my undergraduate degree then went to medical school at the State University of New York at Buffalo. My internship and residency in internal medicine were completed at Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx. I then attended the St. Vincent Medical Center fellowship program for subspecialty training in cardiology at various sites in New York City. When all my training was finally complete in 2006, I moved with my family to Sacramento and joined the Kaiser Permanente team.

profile.title: MD
profile.bio:
I'm originally from the midwest, but came to the Bay Area in 1989 to finish my undergraduate education. I studied Philosophy and Neurobiology at UC Berkeley and thoroughly enjoyed my experience there. I have been in Northern California ever since and consider it my home. I went to medical school at UC Davis and stayed in Sacramento at the UC Davis Medical Center for my residency training. I have been with Kaiser Permanente since finishing my residency training in 2000.

I enjoy the challenge and diversity of problems we face in Emergency Medicine. As Emergency Physicians, we are presented with opportunities to intervene in our patient's lives when their medical problems are often felt most acutely. I feel fortunate to work for an organization like Kaiser that provides it's members with an integrated network for providing a continuity of comprehensive care that I believe is unmatched by most health care systems. Our constantly-evolving health informatics system contributes to this enhanced ability to provide excellent health care to our patients.

In my life outside of medicine, I enjoy traveling, almost any outdoor activity (particularly golf and skiing), and learning new languages.
